# AI-Assisted xv6 Kernel Development

## What This Project Does

This project expands xv6 functionality with the help of an AI debugger.
I implemented 3 features using the AI debugger. Those are:
    - getppid()
        - Returns parent pid just like how getpid() works
    - ps()
        - Prints out every process and their status
        - Walks through every process, prints pid, state, and name
    - lazy sbrk
        - Modifies sbrk to use lazy allocation
        - Only updates process size but does not allocate memory
        - Creates a page fault trap handler to allocate memory if availible
        - Speeds up sbrk because memory is now allocated in the trap handler. This also only gives
          the memory a process requests at the moment.

## How to Build and Run

    ! Must add logcmd to your terminal !
        | If Windows 11:
        | Run command -> notepad $PROFILE
        | Then add this function at the bottom of the notepad
            function logcmd {
                $logfile = "$HOME\xv6_session.log"
                $cmd = $args -join " "
                Add-Content -Path $logfile -Value "$ $cmd"
                & $args[0] $args[1..($args.Length-1)] 2>&1 | Tee-Object -FilePath $logfile -Append
            }
        | Save file then run -> . $PROFILE
    
        | If Mac:
        | Run command -> nano ~/.zshrc
        | Add functio at bottom
            logcmd() {
                local logfile="$HOME/xv6_session.log"
                echo "$ $*" >> "$logfile"
                "$@" 2>&1 | tee -a "$logfile"
            }
        | Save file then reload with -> source ~/.zshrc
    
    1. Run command -> logcmd make qemu-nox
    2. Do what you want in the qemu simulation
    3. run command (MAC) -> python3 Debug.py ~/xv6_session.log "any files you would like"
    3. run command (POWERSHELL) -> python3 Debug.py $HOME/xv6_session.log "any files you would like"

## AI Debugger Tool

A lightweight Python script that captures compiler errors and queries the Claude
API for an explanation. It reads the error output and the relevant source file,
sends both to Claude, and logs the response alongside the actual fix applied.
This produces a record of where AI assistance was accurate and where human
judgment was required.

## What I Learned

    - How xv6 dispatches system calls through a numbered table in syscall.c
    - How the process table is structured and how to safely walk it under a spinlock
    - How virtual memory works in xv6 — page tables, PTEs, physical vs virtual addresses
    - How page faults work at the hardware level and how the kernel handles them
    - The tradeoff between eager and lazy memory allocation and why real operating
      systems like Linux use lazy allocation

## Where AI Helped and Where It Didn't

AI was useful for explaining compiler errors and identifying which kernel subsystem
a bug was coming from. It was less useful for understanding the exact sequence of
changes needed. It was also not very helpful when trying to identify why a triple 
fault was occurring as there is no error output.
